/div><p class=3D"mb15">In what follows we will focus on Bayesian <em>infere=
nce</em>=E2=80=94computing probabilities for hypotheses of interest given d=
ata and other information, including modeling assumptions. Bayesian inferen=
ce is the core of <em>Bayesian data analysis</em> (BDA), comprising the use=
 of Bayesian probability for a broader variety of tasks, including making d=
ecisions (Bayesian decision theory), designing experiments (Bayesian experi=
mental design), and addressing tasks where there is not enough structure fo=
r formal inference (e.g., Bayesian model checking and Bayesian exploratory =
data analysis). Marginalization plays a key role in all of these data analy=
tical activities. The book <em>Bayesian Data Analysis</em> (<a href=3D"http=
s://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/articles/10.3=
389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B29">Gelman et al., 2014a</a>) provides compreh=
ensive coverage of many topics comprising BDA. An emerging term of art, <em=
>Bayesian workflow</em>, refers to best practices for integrating diverse B=
ayesian techniques (including methods fusing Bayesian and frequentist consi=
derations) into robust data analysis pipelines that include model checking =
and refinement steps. <a href=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astro=
nomy-and-space-sciences/articles/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B28">Gelma=
n et al. (2020)</a> provide a broad discussion of Bayesian workflow; <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/arti=
cles/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B56">Tak et al. (2018)</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/artic=
les/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B24">Eadie et al. (2023)</a> discuss ke=
y components of sound Bayesian workflow in astrostatistics.</p><a id=3D"h4"=
