th the hypothesis to the right of the bar). The marginal likelihood works j=
ust like the more familiar parameter likelihood function; =E2=80=9Cmarginal=
=E2=80=9D merely specifies how it is computed. Jack Good has noted that mar=
ginal likelihoods operate just like likelihood functions, calling them <em>=
Bayesian likelihoods</em>. He used <em>weight of evidence</em> for the loga=
rithm of the ratio of marginal likelihoods for two hypotheses (i.e., the lo=
garithm of the <em>Bayes factor</em>), providing an additive (rather than m=
ultiplicative) measure of how much the available evidence favors one hypoth=
esis over the other; the terminology originates with Alan Turing (<a href=
=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/artic=
les/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B33">Good, 1950</a>; <a href=3D"https:/=
/www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/articles/10.3389=
/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B34">1985</a>).</p><p class=3D"editor"><sup><a id=
=3D"fn6" class=3D"color1">6</a></sup>The values of marginal likelihoods dep=
end more sensitively on properties of prior distributions than do posterior=
 PDFs for parameters; in particular, they are roughly inversely proportiona=
l to the prior ranges of parameters. As a result, formal Bayesian model com=
parison and model averaging are best reserved for problems where the analys=
t can strongly motivate priors (especially prior ranges), or quantitatively=
 study how results depend on properties of priors. Good entry points to the=
 literature on this (in both astronomy and statistics) include: <a href=3D"=
https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/articles/=
10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B61">Volinsky et al. (1999)</a>; <a href=3D=
"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/articles=
/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B14">Clyde and George (2004)</a>; <a href=
=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/artic=
les/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B15">Clyde et al. (2007)</a>; <a href=
=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/artic=
les/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B57">Trotta (2012)</a>. For a Bayesian =
perspective on model selection relying on measures of anticipated out-of-sa=
mple predictive performance (vs a priori prediction of the observed sample,=
 as measured by marginal likelihood), see <a href=3D"https://www.frontiersi=
n.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/articles/10.3389/fspas.2024.132=
6926/full#B31">Gelman et al. (2014b)</a>.</p><p class=3D"editor"><sup><a id=
=3D"fn7" class=3D"color1">7</a></sup>Statisticians know this problem as the=
 <em>Neyman-Scott problem</em>, a well-known counterexample to maximum like=
lihood estimation (<a href=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronom=
y-and-space-sciences/articles/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B54">Neyman a=
nd Scott, 1948</a>). Neyman and Scott did important work on statistics in a=
stronomy. Although the Neyman-Scott problem was first described in an econo=
metrics journal, they posed it in terms of measuring =E2=80=9Csome physical=
 constant such as the radial velocity of a star or the velocity of light.=
=E2=80=9D They noted the connection to measurement error problems, and desc=
ribed several settings in astronomy where the issues they addressed potenti=
ally arise. Our discussion here expands on a shorter treatment in <a href=
=3D"https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/astronomy-and-space-sciences/artic=
les/10.3389/fspas.2024.1326926/full#B47">Loredo (2004)</a>.</p><a id=3D"h19=
